<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,654,1382]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,397,731,757]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Characteristics:</emphasis>
(
<number box="[416,428,732,758]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="1.0">1</number>
) Upper frons, vertex and median occipital sclerite black though yellow in 
<taxonomicName box="[1314,1428,732,758]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erectus">
<emphasis box="[1314,1329,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1344,1428,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">erectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; (
<number box="[160,176,770,796]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2.0">2</number>
) Scutum uniformly yellow, brown or black; (
<number box="[728,743,770,796]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="3.0">3</number>
) wings at least slightly infumated but usually intensively brown to blackish; (
<number box="[385,401,809,835]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="4.0">4</number>
) vein R 
<number box="[495,504,825,839]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[513,520,825,839]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="3.0">3</number>
much shorter than Rs and radial triangle (r 
<number box="[1024,1032,825,839]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[1042,1049,825,839]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="3.0">3</number>
) thus higher than crossvein R-M is long, posterior crossvein M-Cu short but distinct 
<figureCitation box="[769,905,850,876]" captionStart="FIGURES 42 – 49. 42 – 43" captionStartId="20.[151,271,1866,1890]" captionTargetBox="[195,1400,204,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[183,1404,194,1840]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 42 – 49. 42 – 43. Ptecticus longipennis (Wiedemann), right wing (42) and medial part of costal margin (43). Scale: 5 mm (42); 0.5 mm (43). 44 – 45. Ptecticus shirakii Nagatomi, right wing (44) and medial part of costal margin (45). Scale: 2 mm (44); 0.5 mm (45). 46 – 47. Ptecticus japonicus (Thunberg), right wing (46) and medial part of costal margin (47). Scale: 5 mm (46); 1 mm (47). 48 – 49. Ptecticus tricolor van der Wulp, right wing (48) and medial part of costal margin (49). Scale: 5 mm (48); 1 mm (49)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186342/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Figs 
<number box="[828,905,850,876]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="46.5" valueMax="47.0" valueMin="46.0">46–47</number>
</figureCitation>
; (
<number box="[928,943,850,876]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="5.0">5</number>
) M 
<number box="[987,995,867,881]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="3.0">3</number>
distinctly sinuate, postcubitus (CuP) strong and pigmented; (
<number box="[445,462,892,918]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="6.0">6</number>
) male cerci unusually elongate and tapered apically, proctiger relatively short, genital capsule subquadrate, gonostylus with distinct lobe on inner side, aedeagal complex rather short and tube-like, gonocoxal apodeme by far not reaching proximal margin of genital capsule but with a distally oriented projection on each side of aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,654,1382]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,322,1047,1073]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Remarks:</emphasis>
A possible synapomorphy is very probably represented by the conspicuously elongated and pointed cerci. This conclusion is also supported by the similarity of other parts of the male terminalia. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitalisi">
<emphasis box="[1413,1428,1086,1111]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,231,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">vitalisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is based on the female 
<typeStatus box="[505,608,1124,1150]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">holotype</typeStatus>
only but apparently it is closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[1109,1222,1124,1150]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erectus">
<emphasis box="[1109,1124,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1138,1222,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">erectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
though the colour of the head parts is only insufficiently described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Brunetti" box="[758,943,1163,1189]" pageId="23" pageNumber="29" refString="Brunetti, E. (1927) Notes on Malayan Diptera, with descriptions of new species. Journal of the Federated Malay States Museums, 13, 281 - 309." type="journal article" year="1927">
Brunetti (
<number box="[870,934,1163,1189]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="1927.0">1927</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,654,1382]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
This species group was known as the 
<taxonomicName box="[642,757,1202,1227]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenebrifer">
<emphasis box="[642,757,1202,1227]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">tenebrifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Rozkosny" box="[897,1201,1202,1228]" pageId="23" pageNumber="30" refString="Rozkosny, R. &amp; Kovac, D. (2000) A revision of the Ptecticus tenebrifer species group (Insecta: Diptera, Stratiomyidae). The Raffless Bulletin of Zoology, 48 (1), 103 - 110." type="journal article" year="2000">
Rozkošný &amp; Kovac 
<number box="[1137,1201,1202,1228]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). However, recently the junior author received a photo (
<figureCitation box="[563,648,1240,1266]" captionStart="FIGURES 50 – 51" captionStartId="21.[151,269,1395,1419]" captionTargetBox="[471,1110,204,1367]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[471,1116,194,1372]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 50 – 51. Holotype of Ptecticus okinawae James (50) and holotype of Ptecticus japonicus Thunberg (51)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186343/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Fig. 
<number box="[618,648,1240,1266]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="51.0">51</number>
</figureCitation>
) of the male 
<typeStatus box="[804,895,1240,1266]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">syntype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Thunberg, 1789" authorityName="Thunberg" authorityYear="1789" box="[935,1317,1240,1266]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[935,1123,1241,1266]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Musca japonica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Thunberg" box="[1130,1317,1240,1266]" pageId="23" pageNumber="30" refString="Thunberg, C. P. (1789) D. D. Museum Naturalium Academiae Upsaliensis. Cujus Partem Septimam. Joh. Edman, Upsaliae, 85 - 94." type="book chapter" year="1789">
Thunberg, 
<quantity box="[1258,1317,1240,1266]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.54406" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="in" value="1789.0">1789</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in perfect condition, which is deposited in 
<collectionCode box="[537,628,1279,1305]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/80z8-1h9s" name="Uppsala University, Zoological Museum" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">UUZM</collectionCode>
. According to the original description this specimen is characterised as “M. antennis setariis nigra, abdomine clavato basi pellucido. Habitat in 
<collectingCountry box="[1027,1120,1318,1344]" name="Japan" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Japonia</collectingCountry>
“ and there is no doubt that it is identical with the syntypic females of 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker, 1849" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1849" box="[649,976,1356,1382]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenebrifer">
<emphasis box="[649,664,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[678,794,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">tenebrifer</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Walker" box="[809,968,1356,1382]" pageId="23" pageNumber="30" refString="Walker, F. (1849) List of the specimens of dipterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Part III. British Museum, London, 485 - 687." type="book chapter" year="1849">
Walker, 
<number box="[908,968,1356,1382]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="1849.0">1849</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rozkosny" box="[1031,1333,1356,1382]" pageId="23" pageNumber="30" refString="Rozkosny, R. &amp; Kovac, D. (2000) A revision of the Ptecticus tenebrifer species group (Insecta: Diptera, Stratiomyidae). The Raffless Bulletin of Zoology, 48 (1), 103 - 110." type="journal article" year="2000">
Rozkošný &amp; Kovac 
<number box="[1269,1333,1356,1382]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
